solutions.content:
# Intuition:
Very simple once you understand the description.
The frog starts at index 0.
In every input case, it will first take 1 unit jump. Therefore, it will go from 0 to 1. So, if any input case doesn't contain `stones[1] = 1`, we directly return false. Because, the frog wont be able to take 1 unit of jump initially.
Then when, it is in index i, it has 3 options to choose: (assume previous jump was 1 unit and current stone value = 2)
- it can jump to `current stone + (previous unit - 1)` stone if exists.
- it can jump to `current stone + previous unit` stone if exists.
- it can jump to `current stone + (previous unit + 1)` stone if exists.
- If the frog reaches `idx == n-1` it reaches the end. We `return true`.

# Using Binary Search:
``` java []
class Solution {
    int n;
    Boolean[][] memo;
    public boolean canCross(int[] stones) {
        n = stones.length;
        if(stones[1]!=1) {
            return false;
        }
        memo = new Boolean[2001][2001];
        return helper(1, 1, stones);
    }
    boolean helper(int idx, int prevUnit, int[] stones) {
        if(idx == n-1) {
            return true;
        }
        if(memo[idx][prevUnit]!=null) {
            return memo[idx][prevUnit];
        }
        boolean ans = false;
        for(int nextJump = prevUnit-1; nextJump<=prevUnit+1 && !ans; nextJump++) {
            if(nextJump>0) {
                int nextStone = stones[idx]+nextJump;
                int nextIdx = binSearch(idx, stones, nextStone);
                if(nextIdx!=-1) {
                    ans = ans || helper(nextIdx, nextJump, stones);
                }
            }
        }
        return memo[idx][prevUnit] = ans;
    }

    int binSearch(int idx, int[] stones, int target) {
        int left = idx;
        int right = n-1;
        while(left <= right) {
            int mid = right - (right-left)/2;
            if(stones[mid] == target) {
                return mid;
            }
            else if(stones[mid]>target) {
                right = mid-1;
            }
            else {
                left = mid+1;
            }
        }
        return -1;
    }
}
```

# Complexity Analysis:

Here, $N$ is the number of stones in the river.
- Time Complexity: $O(N^2 \log N)$
$O(N^2)$ for recursion with memoization. Additional $\log N$ is because we do binary search.

- Space Complexity: $O(N^2)$
The array `Boolean[][] memo` will take $N^2$ space.


# Using HashMap:

``` java []
class Solution {
    int n;
    Boolean[][] memo;
    Map<Integer, Integer> mp;
    public boolean canCross(int[] stones) {
        n = stones.length;
        if(stones[1]!=1) {
            return false;
        }
        memo = new Boolean[2001][2001];
        mp = new HashMap<>();
        for(int i=0; i<n; i++) {
            mp.put(stones[i], i);
        }
        return helper(1, 1, stones);
    }
    boolean helper(int idx, int prevUnit, int[] stones) {
        if(idx == n-1) {
            return true;
        }
        if(memo[idx][prevUnit]!=null) {
            return memo[idx][prevUnit];
        }
        boolean ans = false;
        for(int nextJump = prevUnit-1; nextJump<=prevUnit+1 && !ans; nextJump++) {
            if(nextJump > 0) {
                int nextStone = stones[idx]+nextJump;
                if(mp.containsKey(nextStone)) {
                    ans = ans || helper(mp.get(nextStone), nextJump, stones);
                }
            }
        }
        return memo[idx][prevUnit] = ans;
    }
}
```

# Complexity Analysis:

Here, $N$ is the number of stones in the river.
- Time Complexity: $O(N^2)$
$O(N^2)$ for recursion with memoization.

- Space Complexity: $O(N^2)$
The array `Boolean[][] memo` and `HashMap<Integer, Integer>` will take $N^2$ space.

