solutions.content:
# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The first thought that comes to mind is that we have to try out all the possible paths through which we can reach the last stone. And the easiest way to try out all the paths is through recursion. Now if we try to draw the recursion tree we will see that there are many repeatations, so we can try the memoize the results using DP. 

And as the array is sorted to know the next index where we can move, considering all the constraints, we can use binary search(upper_bound and lower_bound). I will elaborate on this in the approach section.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
From any position we can go to (pos + (k - 1)), (pos + k) and (pos + (k + 1)) considering previous jump was of k steps. Now if we are a at an index we can go the a number of indices. we can use the concept of lower bound and upper bound in this (ub and lb explained below). If you don't have idea about ub and lb, I would recommand you to give it a read because it comes handy in many situations.

`ind1 = lower_bound(pos + (k - 1))` : this will give the first index that has value >= (pos + (k - 1)). Now it might cross (pos + (k + 1)) if no value in the permissable range is present. and in that case ind2 will also point to same index.

`ind2 = upper_bound(pos + (k + 1))` : this will give the first index that has value > (pos + (k + 1)). So we can't go upto this index. we have to stop before this.

If no value in the permissable range is present then both will point to the same index. So in that case no recursion call happens because we are running loop from (ind1 to ind2 - 1). otherwise recursion call for all possible permissable index will be made. 

`min_steps = max(1, prev_step - 1)` is taken becasue no backward movement is allowed and if min_steps == 0 then we will stay at the same index which makes no sense.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
**$$O(3 * n)$$**
considering n is the size of the stones array.
Bacause for every index we can take k - 1 , k and k + 1 step. so there are maximum 3 possibility for every index.

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
**$$O(n * n)$$**
as we are using a n * n dp array. 
if we keep of taking prev_step + 1 step for every index then we might end up taking n step for the last index so so we have to take n * n array.

# Code
```
class Solution {
private:
    bool can(int ind, int prev_step, vector<int> &stones, vector<vector<int>> &dp) {
        if(ind == stones.size() - 1) return true;

        if(dp[ind][prev_step] != -1) return dp[ind][prev_step];

        int min_step = max(1, prev_step - 1);
        int max_step = prev_step + 1;

        int ind1 = lower_bound(stones.begin(), stones.end(), stones[ind] + min_step) - stones.begin();
        int ind2 = upper_bound(stones.begin(), stones.end(), stones[ind] + max_step) - stones.begin();

        bool res = false;
        for(int i = ind1; i < ind2; i++) {
            res = res || can(i, stones[i] - stones[ind], stones, dp);
        }
        return dp[ind][prev_step] = res;
    }

public:
    bool canCross(vector<int>& stones) {
        vector<vector<int>> dp(stones.size(), vector<int> (stones.size(), -1));
        return can(0, 0, stones, dp);
    }
};
