# Intuition
As stated you will always have `1` step and $$1st$$ stone is `0` with that you can reach $$2nd$$ stone BUT!!! the catch here is you can reach that stone only if the $$2nd$$ stone is 1, since clearly stated that 

```
next_stone = curr_stone + past_jumps
```
So let's remove the possibility such that $$2nd$$ stone is greater than `1`, where you will never reach the last stone.

And then try out all possible ways to to reach last stone using **Recursion**. 

# Approach-1 Recursion (OBVIOUS TLE)

In Recursion, We try out all possible ways at each state by checking whether with the `prev_jump` and `curr_stone` we are able to reach the `last_stone`.

At any state when we cross the stones without reaching `last_stone` situated at `n-1`, we consider it as **not reaching**.
So our Base case is defined as below

```
if(i >= n)
{
    return false;   // Not Reached
}
if(i == n-1)
{
    return true;    // Reached
}
```

Now At any state, we try out simple recursion with `prev_jump-1`, `prev_jump`, `prev_jump+1` with `curr_stone`.

As stated the frog can jump to a stone with `curr_stone + prev_jump` value, we try to find a stone such that `new_stone = curr_stone + prev_jump` 

I've generalized those jumps using a *for loop*.

```
for(int& t: jumps)
{
    int jump = prev + t;
    for(int j=i+1; j<n; j++)
    {
        if(curr + jump == new_stone in nums)
        {
            // Check for the curr_stone + prev_jump
        }
    }
}
```

# Code

