# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Use recursion with meomory to solve. That is DP. Since stones is in ascending order, one approach is using binary search to find the next stone for frog jump. 2nd approach a hash table is established without BS.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
[Please turn English subtitles if neccessary]
[https://youtu.be/IkUmZHbsyl0?si=pAF9VqtXj8ordm2t](https://youtu.be/IkUmZHbsyl0?si=pAF9VqtXj8ordm2t)
The code uses DP approach to solve the frog river crossing problem. 

The 2D dp[i][k] matrix is indexed by (index for stone, jump units).
It maintains a 2D dp matrix to store results. The recursive function f explores possible jump units and uses binary search to find the next stone the frog can jump to. Consider dp[next][jump] where stones[next]=stones[i]+jump & jump=k-1, k, k+1.

The results of subproblems are memoized in the dp matrix to avoid redundant calculations. 
![frogJimp.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/c2b8edf1-82d2-4582-82f8-860f417a8947_1693113731.635507.png)

2 approaches have the similar speed behaviors, although the code using hash table has smaller time complexity!

# Code using binary search Runtime 36 ms Beats 98.48%
```
class Solution {
public:
    int n;
    vector<vector<int>> dp; //2D dp matrix (index for stone, jump units)
    bool f(vector<int>& stones, int i, int k){
        if (i==n-1) return 1;
        if (dp[i][k]!=-1) return dp[i][k];
        bool ans=0;
        for(int jump: {k-1, k, k+1}){//possible jump units: k-1, k, k+1
            if (jump==0) continue;
            //Use binary search, since stones[i] is ascending
            int next=lower_bound(stones.begin()+(i+1), stones.end(), stones[i]+jump)
                -stones.begin();
            if (next==n || stones[next]!=stones[i]+jump) continue; // not found
            ans=ans||f(stones, next, jump);
        }
        return dp[i][k]=ans;
    }

    bool canCross(vector<int>& stones) {
        n=stones.size();
        dp.assign(n+1, vector<int>(n+1, -1));
        return f(stones, 0, 0); 
    }
};
```
