**Approach**

1. Make a hashmap of each stone, which would contain a set. That set would store the viable jump sizes that could be used to reach at that stone. E.g.: Initially 2nd stone, it would be 1 only.
2. Initially setting 1 jump for stone[0], since we can jump only 1 unit at first.
3. Traverse the stone array from 0th index (1st stone). That can be the next position of frog.
4. Populate the sets of stones that can be reached from current position using a viable jump size (that is k - 1 or k or k + 1). Next Viable jump size can be calculated from previous jump size, and this previous jump size would be found in set of current position.
5. Return true if we reaches to the last stone, that means we can reach to the destinition, otherwise false.

```
class Solution {
public:
    bool canCross(vector<int>& stones) 
    {
        map<int, set<int>>mp;

        for(int i = 0 ; i<stones.size() ; i++)
        {
            mp[stones[i]] = {};  //Initially providing empty set (no jumps).
        }

        mp[stones[0]].insert(1) ;  //Initially we can take only 1 unit of jump to reach at next stone.


        for(int i = 0 ; i<stones.size() ; i++)
        {
            int currentStone = stones[i] ; 
            set<int>jumps = mp[currentStone];
            for(auto j : jumps)
            {

                int pos = j + currentStone ; 

                if(pos == stones[stones.size() - 1])    //let's check if we have reached to the last stone or not if yes then congratulations return true.
                {
                    return true;
                }
                else if(mp.find(pos) != mp.end())    //think if the taken jump allow us to stand at the next stone if yes then do set the jumps to travel for next stone.
                {
                    if(j - 1 > 0)
                    {
                        mp[pos].insert(j-1);
                    }
                    mp[pos].insert(j);
                    mp[pos].insert(j+1);
                }
            }
        }

        return false;    //return false if we haven't reached to the last stone.
    }
};
```

