![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/d58229d9-c040-4640-ade4-904e9762bbc1_1693119860.1054668.png)
I haven't seen any faster solution so far, so I post my solution here for those who want a really fast algorithm.
# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
> If the frog's last jump was k units, its next jump must be either k - 1, k, or k + 1 units. The frog can only jump in the forward direction.

By reading the problem description, we can easily see that every jump is dependent on the last jump, such that `|currJump - lastJump| <= 1`.
In other words, for every last jump, there are three possible next jump, respectively `lastJump - 1`, `lastJump` and `lastJump + 1`.
One of the most important techniques in computer sicience to solve a problem is to break it down to smaller problems and deal with one small problem each time.
The key here is to look at only one jump each time, so that we don't get confused.
# Approach : Top-Down Dynamic Programming
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Consider the case where the frog jumps into `stone` with `lastJump`, where `stone` denotes the index of the current stone in the array `stones`.
If `stone` is already the last stone in the `stones` array, it means we've cross the river. Therefore we return `ture`.
```
if (stone >= stones.length - 1) return true;
```
If `stone` is not the last stone, we set `nextStone` to be `stone + 1`. By doing so, we do not allow jumping over and over again to `stone` with zero distance.
```
int nextStone = stone + 1;
```
Since the least units we can jump is `lastJump - 1`, we can skip all the stones that are less than `stones[stone] + lastJump - 1`.
```
while (nextStone < stones.length 
        && stones[nextStone] < stones[stone] + lastJump - 1)
    nextStone++;
```
Now we have `stones[nextStone] >= stones[stone] + lastJump - 1`. It's time to consider three different jumps `{lastJump - 1, lastJump, lastJump + 1}`.
- **Consider `jump - 1`**
If `stones[nextStone] == stones[stone] + lastJump - 1`, then we jump to `nextStone` and skip one stone. Now we have `stones[nextStone] >= stones[stone] + lastJump`.
Else, `stones[nextStone] > stones[stone] + lastJump - 1`, it is the same as `stones[nextStone] >= stones[stone] + lastJump`. We do nothing.
    ```
    if (nextStone < stones.length && stones[nextStone] == stones[stone] + lastJump - 1)
        if (canCross(nextStone, lastJump - 1))
            return true;
        nextStone++;
    ```

- **Consider `jump`**
If `stones[nextStone] == stones[stone] + lastJump`, then we jump to `nextStone` and skip one stone. Now we have `stones[nextStone] >= stones[stone] + lastJump + 1`.
Else, `stones[nextStone] > stones[stone] + lastJump`, it is the same as `stones[nextStone] >= stones[stone] + lastJump + 1`. We do nothing.
    ```
    if (nextStone < stones.length && stones[nextStone] == stones[stone] + lastJump)
        if (canCross(nextStone, lastJump))
            return true;
        nextStone++;
    ```
- **Consider `jump + 1`**
If `stones[nextStone] == stones[stone] + lastJump + 1`, then we jump to `nextStone`.
    ```
    if (nextStone < stones.length && stones[nextStone] == stones[stone] + lastJump + 1)
        if (canCross(nextStone, lastJump + 1))
            return true;
    ```
If none of the three jumps can make it, we return false.

---

> The approach above can logically solve the problem already, but the complexity will be O(3<sup>n</sup>) since in worse case we recursively look at three different jumps each time. If one submit the approach above, the result will be TLE.
That's why introduce memorization, aka DP.

Since there can potantially be many overlaps in recursive calls for (`stone`, `lastJump`).
We keep track of all the visited compinations of (`stone`, `lastJump`) by using a two-dimensional boolean array `boolean[][] visited`.
When we first visit a combination of (`stone`, `lastJump`), we set `visited[stone][lastJump]` to `true`.
If we ever visit a combination that we've visited before, it means this very combination can not cross, otherwise we would've return `true` already;
```
if (visited[stone][lastJump]) return false;
visited[stone][lastJump] = true;
```

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n<sup>2</sup>)
In worse case senario, we make recursive calls for all the possible combination of (`stone`, `lastJump`) and fill up `visited`. Hence O(n<sup>2</sup>).
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(n<sup>2</sup>)
We need O(n<sup>2</sup>) space for the two-dimensional boolean array `visited`.
In worse case senario, the maximum depth for recursive calls is O(n). Hence we need O(n) for recursion stack.
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
    int[] stones;
    boolean[][] visited;
    public boolean canCross(int[] stones) {
        if (stones[1] != 1 || stones[stones.length - 1] > 2001000)
            return false;
        this.stones = stones;
        visited = new boolean[stones.length][stones.length];
        return canCross(1, 1);
    }
    public boolean canCross(int stone, int lastJump) {
        // River Crossed!
        if (stone >= stones.length - 1) return true;

        if (visited[stone][lastJump]) return false;
        visited[stone][lastJump] = true;

        int nextStone = stone + 1;
        while (nextStone < stones.length && stones[nextStone] < stones[stone] + lastJump - 1)
            nextStone++;

        // Consider lastJump - 1
        if (nextStone < stones.length && stones[nextStone] == stones[stone] + lastJump - 1 
                && canCross(nextStone++, lastJump - 1))
            return true;
        // Consider lastJump
        if (nextStone < stones.length && stones[nextStone] == stones[stone] + lastJump 
                && canCross(nextStone++, lastJump))
            return true;
        // Consider lastJump + 1
        return nextStone < stones.length && stones[nextStone] == stones[stone] + lastJump + 1
                && canCross(nextStone, lastJump + 1);
    }
}
